@node "Function plotter" "Funtion plotter"
@{b}@{u}Function plotter.@{ub}@{uu}

With function plotter it's possible to create all kinds of mathematic
curves. For example sinewave could easily be created with formula sin(x).

In the function plotter window is several gadgets, here are their names and
explanations:

Function plotter window contains several gadgets. Gadget names and
explanations:

@{u}* f(x)=@{uu}

String gadget used to input mathematic formulas. Accepts following
functions:

 * Trigonometric (all functions use radians as their input values):

   - sin() sine.
   - cos() cosine.
   - tan() tangent.
   - asin() arcus sine.
   - acos() arcus cosine.
   - atan() arcus tangent.
   - sinh() hyperbolic sine.
   - cosh() hyperbolic cosine.
   - tanh() hyperbolic tangent.

 * Other mathematical functions:

   - exp() exponential of e.
   - ln() natural logarithm.
   - log() logarithm base of 10.
   - sqrt() or sqr() squareroot.

 * Other "functions" for convenience (returnvalue range: -1 to 1):

   - square() makes a square wave from radian values.
   - saw() makes a sawtooth wave.
   - triangle() makes a triangle wave.
   - runup() runs up from 0 at input of 0 to 1 at input of 2*pi.

 * Mathematic constants:

   - pi
   - e

 * variables:

   - x is 0 at beginning and runs up to 2pi (full radian cycle).
   - pos gives the position of the sample currently being calculated.
     (from 1 to 8).

@{u}* Calculation mode:@{uu}

This cycle gadget offers three types of calculation:

 * Fit: Fits the wave to full amplitude range from -128 to +127.
 * Cycle: Values over the maximum amplitude will be appear at the bottom
   and below the minimum they will appear at the top
 * Cut: All values going outside the amplitude range will be cut to the
   maximum/minimum values.

@{u}* Calculate!@{uu}

Starts the calculation and sets up the new wave as a tuning tone.

@{u}* Load@{uu}

Loads a formula from file. Note that this accepts any file. If it's binary
file, it'll certainly give a weird formula. Formulas can not be longer than
80 characters, if file is longer, only 80 chars will be loaded.

@{u}* Save@{uu}

Saves current formula to file as ascii text.


Always use x or pos for formulas. Otherwise you will get a straight line at
some amplitude value. All functions, variables and constants are case
insensitive.

Examples:

 sin(x)              Sinewave.
 triangle(x)         Trianglewave.
 sin(x*2)            Double-frequency sinewave.
 sin(x)+sin(x*2)/2   double frequency sinewave added to normal frequency
                     wave at half amplitude. (sounds as if you have two
                     frequencies simultaneously playing).
@endnode

@node "Fast scope" "Fast scope"
@{b}@{u}Fast scope@{ub}@{uu}

Fast scope is used to show a realtime situation of the sampled signal.
Updateoccurs everry time the screen is drawn. (this is affected heavily by
the screen mode you are working on) Length of the displayed wave is one
complete cycle.

The main advance of the Fast Scope, is very fine tuning of an instrument.
It's used this way:

If the @{"levelmeter" link "Meters" 0} is showing that the instrument is almost at correct
frequency, you should also look at this scope. Scope shows some of the
following situations:

* Wave stays still, and only little 'living' is happening on it:
 Instrument is perfectly tuned.

* Wave is moving left:
 Instrument is tuned too high.

* Wave is moving right:
 Instrument is tuned too low.


Scope also shows the current level of signal.
@endnode

@node "Slower scope" "Slower scope"
@{b}@{u}Slower scope@{ub}@{uu}

With this you can coarse tune an instrument. It shows 8 cycles of the wave
simultaneously. The actual waveform is drawn at the foreground. Below this
wave is wave, which is copied from the first cycle to all cycles following
it. This can be read from the display:


* The foreground wave is at the same positions with the background wave:

Instrument is perfectly tuned.


* The foreground wave is getting more to the left as background wave:

Instrument is tuned too high.


* The foreground wave is getting more to the right as background wave:

Instrument is tuned too low.
@endnode

@node "Meters" "Meters"
@{b}@{u}Meters@{ub}@{uu}

Three kinds of meters are implemented with Perfect Pitch. They are all shown
in the "meter" window. There are the explanations for them:

* Levelmeter:

Shows a very visual sight of frequency difference between the right
frequency and one coming from the sampler. If it is at the left side,
frequency of incoming signal is too low. at center, the tuning is perfect.
(But you can still tune it even better with @{"fast scope" link "Fast scope" 0}) If it's at the right
side, frequency is too high.

* Difference in hertz:

This does just what it says there.

* Percent difference:

As does this.
@endnode

@node "Wave editor" "Wave editor"
@{b}@{u}Wave editor.@{ub}@{uu}

With wave editor, it's possible to create any types of tuning waveforms. In
Perfect Pitch sample lenght is limited to 8 samples. This, however is enough
for this type of application.

Gadgets and their explanations:

* Wave display:

Main area for editing the sound. Just press mouse button over it and you
will see what happens. It can also be controlled by keyboard. Just activate
the editor for keyboard input by pressing tab-key several times. Here are
the keyboard controls:

 - Right arrow: next sample.

 - Left arrow: previous sample.

 - Up arrow: increase the amplitude of current sample.

 - Down arrow: decrease the amplitude of current sample.

 - Shift-up: increase the amplitude of current sample by 10.

 - Shift-down: decrease the amplitude of current sample by 10.


Current sample position is indicated by different color (adjustable via
prefs window).


Gadgets in "Working mode" area:

* Grid:

Enables the vertical lines for different sample positions.

* Continuous capturing:

Enables the "continuous capturing"-mode. When activated, the wave display
area is disabled and tuning tone waveforms are continuously got from the
sampler. Interval betveen captures can be adjusted by "Capture
interval"-gadget (explained later).

* Volume:

Adjusts volume between 0 (quiet) and 64 (full volume).

* Capture interval:

Shows the interval betveen captures in "continuous capturing"-mode. Tenths
of second.


Gadgets in "Edit"-area:

* Flip x:

Flips the wave around x-axis.

* Flip y:

Flips the wave around y-axis.

* Maximize:

Stretches the wave to fullfill the amplitude range.

* Capture:

Captures one cycle of waveform from the sampler.

* Plotter:

Opens the @{"plotter" link "Function plotter" 0} window.


Gadgets in "File area":

* Load:

Pops up the file requester to choose file from.

* Save:

Pops up the file requester to choose file from. Note that any file is
allowed to load, only 8 first bytes will be read.
@endnode

