@node "List" "List"
@{b}@{u}List@{ub}@{uu}

By list window you can define some special notes or frequencies. Handy, for
example, for defining the guitar string frequencies.

* List:

Here is the list of predefined notes. Just double-click some entry to make
it active. Also MUI's drag'n'drop facilities can be used to sort the list.


Gadgets in "Edit"-area:

* String-gadget:

Defines the name of the entry to be created with "New"-button.

* New:

Creates the new entry. Name is taken from the above string-gadget. Current
frequency setting will be saved to the entry.

* Remove:

Removes the active entry.


Gadgets in "File"-area:

* Load:

Pops up the file requester to choose file from.

* Save:

Pops up the filerequester to choose filename from.
@endnode

@node "Keyboard" "Keyboard"
@{b}@{u}Keyboard@{ub}@{uu}

This window is for setting the frequency of current string.

* Keyboard:

Just use your mouse by pressing left button at the note you want or use a
keyboard. For keyboard control just press "tab" key until keyboard is
active. Then press right or left cursor keys to adjust the note.

* Octave slider:

Current octave.

* Frequency:

Frequency of currently selected note. You can also enter here any frequency
you want (betveen 10 and 2000 Hz).
@endnode

@node "Preferences" "Preferences"
@{b}@{u}Preferences@{ub}@{uu}

Four pages are created at preferences window.

* Colors-page:

Here you can define the drawing pens for all non-@{"MUI" link "MUI" 0} gadgets. MUI's
drag'n'drop facilities can be used betveen colorfields.

* Sampler-page:

Here you can define the states of parallel port control lines. Usually
"Paper out" and "Select" -signals are used for selecting the channel of
stereo samplers. Busy may be overflow-indicator of the sampler, so it should
be "input". If your sampler doesn't work with default settings, just test,
when it starts to work.

* Directories-page:

Here you can set the initial files for @{"wave" link "Wave editor" 0}, @{"plotter" link "Function plotter" 0} function, @{"list" link "List" 0} and
@{"keyfile" link "Distribution" 0}.

Also online-help file is defined here. When you adjust this, you should test
the new setting with "HELP"-key. Amigaguide help should appear.

* Misc-page:

Filter is for enabling or disabling the lowpass filter of the machine. With
NTSC-button you can set the TRUE crystal frequency of the machine. Usually
it is defined right at startup, but if you use bootmenu or something else,
which changes GfxBase->DisplayFlags, you should set this to the right value.
@endnode

@node "About" "About Perfect Pitch"
@{b}@{u}What is this.@{ub}@{uu}

Have you ever wondered, how to tune your instrument? You have an Amiga
computer at your desk? And a parallel port sampler? This thing is just what
you have been waiting for! All you have to do, is to put the microphone from
your instrument to your sampler's input and start this program. Just read
following sections of this guide and your instrument is in Perfect Pitch!

Stay tuned!
@endnode

